    num:"F4", title:"Sarasvathy's Effectuation", unit:1, slibrary:1, pedagogy:"Presentation",
    author:"Saras Sarasvathy (2001)",
    summary:"Five principles describing how expert entrepreneurs decide under uncertainty.",
    professionalDefinition:"Effectuation is a logic of decision-making characterised by five interlocking principles — bird-in-hand, affordable loss, lemonade, crazy quilt, and pilot-in-the-plane — that expert entrepreneurs use under conditions of true (Knightian) uncertainty (Sarasvathy, 2001). Goals emerge from available means rather than means being chosen to achieve pre-given goals.",
    whoDeveloped:"Saras D. Sarasvathy (b. 1959), Paul Hammaker Professor at the Darden School of Business, University of Virginia. Trained under Herbert Simon at Carnegie Mellon, Sarasvathy interviewed 27 expert entrepreneurs (each having built at least one company past USD 200m) and extracted the recurring decision logic that became Effectuation.",
    whyDeveloped:"Standard MBA training presumes goals are given and means are chosen — a 'causal' logic that breaks down under genuine uncertainty. Sarasvathy sought a behaviourally accurate alternative: how do successful entrepreneurs actually decide when forecasts are unreliable?",
    howToApply:[
      "Inventory means: who you are, what you know, whom you know",
      "Define affordable loss for the next 90 days (money, time, reputation)",
      "Begin the smallest action that nets a stakeholder commitment",
      "Treat surprise as material rather than failure (the 'lemonade' principle)",
      "Build with anyone willing to commit, not with whom you wished would"
    ],
