    summary:"Innovators · Early Adopters · Early Majority · Late Majority · Laggards.",
    professionalDefinition:"Diffusion of Innovations is a sociological theory of how, why and at what rate new ideas and technologies spread through a social system, classifying adopters into five categories (Innovators 2.5%, Early Adopters 13.5%, Early Majority 34%, Late Majority 34%, Laggards 16%) and identifying five attributes that affect adoption rate (Rogers, 1962).",
    whoDeveloped:"Everett M. Rogers (1931–2004), American sociologist and communication theorist at Iowa State, Stanford, and the University of New Mexico. Diffusion of Innovations was first published in 1962, with the fifth and final edition in 2003. Rogers drew on hybrid corn adoption studies among Iowa farmers in the 1950s.",
    whyDeveloped:"Rogers sought a unified theory of how innovations spread, drawing on agricultural economics, public health, communication studies and sociology. His 5,000+ studies-deep meta-analysis identified consistent patterns across very different contexts (technology, medical practices, agricultural methods).",
