    whyDeveloped:"Founders consistently inflated market sizes by quoting only the largest available number. Investors needed a discipline that distinguished the universe (TAM), the realistic addressable subset (SAM), and the achievable target (SOM) — making founder claims testable.",
    howToApply:[
      "Estimate TAM top-down using industry data",
      "Estimate SAM bottom-up using your channels and geography",
      "Estimate SOM realistically using your traction × time × competition",
      "Show your working — the calculation matters more than the number",
      "Update annually or after major market events"
    ],
    whenToUse:"In pitch decks, business plans, board briefings, and any time you claim 'this is a $X billion market'.",
    byWhom:"Founders, VCs, strategy consultants, M&A advisors, and corporate-development teams.",
    innovation:"Compared with single-number market sizing, TAM-SAM-SOM forces a hierarchy of plausibility. Compared with bottom-up cohort modelling alone, it preserves the strategic question 'how big could this become' alongside 'how big can we realistically get'.",
    figureCaption:"Three concentric circles labelled TAM (outermost), SAM (middle), SOM (innermost) with sample numbers showing each tier shrinking by an order of magnitude.",
