    professionalDefinition:"Mintzberg's 5 Ps of Strategy is a meta-definition of strategy that recognises five compatible meanings used in practice: Plan (intended action), Ploy (a manoeuvre to outwit competition), Pattern (consistency in a stream of decisions), Position (a place in the market relative to competitors), and Perspective (an organisational worldview) (Mintzberg, 1987).",
    whoDeveloped:"Henry Mintzberg (b. 1939), Cleghorn Professor of Management Studies at McGill University, introduced the 5 Ps in 'The Strategy Concept I: Five Ps for Strategy' (California Management Review, 1987). The framework distilled three decades of his strategy research, much of which had questioned the dominant Porter-style positioning view.",
