    summary:"Stars · Cash Cows · Question Marks · Dogs — portfolio thinking.",
    professionalDefinition:"The Growth-Share Matrix is a portfolio-management tool that classifies a firm's businesses or products into a 2×2 grid defined by relative market share (high vs low) and market growth rate (high vs low), yielding four cells — Stars, Cash Cows, Question Marks, and Dogs — each with distinct cash-flow and resource-allocation implications (Henderson, 1970).",
    whoDeveloped:"Bruce D. Henderson (1915–1992), founder of the Boston Consulting Group (BCG), introduced the matrix in BCG's 1970 client publication. The framework distilled BCG's earlier work on the experience curve and the rule of three-and-four with a memorable visual device.",
