    num:"F32", title:"Moore's Bowling Alley", unit:4, slibrary:8, pedagogy:"Hackathon",
    author:"Geoffrey Moore (1995)",
    summary:"Win one beachhead, then knock down adjacent pins.",
    professionalDefinition:"The Bowling Alley is a market-development sequencing model for high-tech products, in which a beachhead segment is dominated first ('the head pin'), and dominance is then leveraged into adjacent segments ('the next pin') via shared customer references, distribution channels, and 'whole product' completeness (Moore, 1995).",
    whoDeveloped:"Geoffrey A. Moore (b. 1946) introduced the Bowling Alley as the post-chasm sequencing model in Inside the Tornado (1995), the sequel to Crossing the Chasm (1991). Moore's consulting work with high-tech clients in the 1990s validated the framework across software, hardware and biotech contexts.",
    whyDeveloped:"After helping clients cross the chasm to early-majority adoption, Moore observed that some succeeded at expanding to mainstream while others stalled. He sought to identify the sequencing that consistently produced expansion — and found that pragmatist segments adopted in clusters defined by shared 'whole product' needs.",
    howToApply:[
      "Pick one beachhead pin (segment) and dominate it",
      "Identify adjacent pins (similar use case, similar buyer, can leverage same whole product)",
      "Use beachhead reference customers to convert adjacent pins",
      "Re-sequence as data emerges — adjacency assumptions are testable",
      "Avoid premature broadening — staying focused longer is usually right"
    ],
    whenToUse:"Post-chasm growth strategy in B2B technology, enterprise software, deep-tech ventures, and any context where reference customers materially influence adoption.",
    byWhom:"B2B SaaS founders, enterprise sales leaders, deep-tech ventures (especially with adjacent verticals), VCs, and growth strategists.",
    innovation:"Compared with broad-based mainstream marketing, the Bowling Alley prescribes sequenced focus — extending Moore's chasm-crossing logic into the early-majority segment. Compared with Ansoff's growth matrix (which considers product/market dimensions abstractly), the Bowling Alley specifies the order of expansion.",
    figureCaption:"A bowling alley with the head pin (beachhead) and several second-row pins (adjacent segments), each pin labelled with a customer-segment archetype; the ball carries the firm's brand.",
    related:["F15","F22","F53"],
