    professionalDefinition:"A North Star Metric is a single quantitative measure that captures the core value the product delivers to customers and predicts long-term revenue, used as the anchor of operational dashboards, prioritisation decisions and team alignment (Ellis, ~2010s; Burnes & Lessin, 2018).",
    whoDeveloped:"Sean Ellis, founder of GrowthHackers and previously growth lead at Dropbox, popularised the term in industry articles in the 2010s. Josh Burnes and Sam Lessin formalised the methodology in Amplitude's North Star Playbook (2018). The concept built on existing 'one metric that matters' literature in product management.",
    whyDeveloped:"Ellis observed that fast-growing technology companies anchored their teams on a single value-capturing metric (Airbnb → nights booked; Spotify → time listening; Slack → messages sent), whereas slower-growing companies tracked dozens of metrics and prioritised inconsistently. The North Star formalised the discipline.",
