    author:"Peter Drucker",
    summary:"Invention creates novelty; innovation creates value.",
    professionalDefinition:"Drucker's Innovation vs Invention distinction holds that invention is the act of creating something novel, while innovation is the disciplined process of converting that novelty into customer-recognised, market-validated value — a distinction that explains why most inventions never become innovations and why innovation is a managerial discipline rather than a creative event (Drucker, 1985).",
    whoDeveloped:"Peter F. Drucker (see F3). The invention-vs-innovation distinction runs through Drucker's writing from the 1950s onward but is most explicitly developed in Innovation and Entrepreneurship (1985) and Management Challenges for the 21st Century (1999).",
