    byWhom:"CEOs, board members, executive coaches, succession-planning consultants, and leadership educators.",
    innovation:"Compared with previous management bestsellers (often founder-driven anecdotes), Good to Great applied rigorous empirical criteria. Compared with Built to Last (Collins & Porras, F6), Good to Great focuses on the transition rather than the maintenance of greatness. Caveat: some 'great' companies in the original study (Circuit City, Fannie Mae) later declined sharply.",
    figureCaption:"A flywheel diagram with seven curved spokes labelled with the seven concepts; arrows show momentum building as each concept reinforces the next, accelerating outperformance.",
