    professionalDefinition:"The Bootstrapping Ladder is a stage-sequenced model of funding sources used by founders building businesses without external equity capital, ascending from personal savings and sweat equity through customer pre-payments, supplier credit, factoring and asset-light service revenue, with each rung preserving founder ownership and operational control (industry practice; Gianforte, 2005).",
    whoDeveloped:"No single attributable author. The ladder concept emerged in entrepreneurship-practice literature in the 1990s–2000s, with Greg Gianforte's Bootstrapping Your Business: Start-Up to $200M+ Without Investors (2005) as a foundational practitioner text. Earlier academic foundations include Bhide's Origin and Evolution of New Businesses (2000).",
