    num:"F64", title:"Y Combinator SAFE", unit:8, slibrary:16, pedagogy:"Hackathon",
    author:"Carolynn Levy / Y Combinator (2013)",
    summary:"Simple Agreement for Future Equity — no interest, no maturity, valuation cap and discount.",
    professionalDefinition:"The Y Combinator SAFE (Simple Agreement for Future Equity) is a financing instrument that converts to equity at a future priced round at either a pre-set valuation cap or a discount (whichever is more favourable to the investor), with no interest, no maturity date, and no legal entitlement to convert if no priced round occurs — designed to simplify and accelerate early-stage financing (Y Combinator, 2013, updated 2018).",
    whoDeveloped:"Carolynn Levy, partner at Y Combinator, drafted the original SAFE in 2013. The post-money SAFE (2018) updated the instrument to clarify dilution mechanics. The SAFE templates are publicly available at ycombinator.com/documents and have been adapted (with permission) by accelerators worldwide.",
    whyDeveloped:"Convertible notes — the prior standard for early-stage rounds — accumulated interest, had maturity dates, and required periodic renegotiation. The SAFE eliminated those features to reduce founder anxiety and legal cost, accepting in exchange the loss of investor downside protection.",
    howToApply:[
      "Use the standard YC SAFE templates",
      "Set a realistic valuation cap (the maximum valuation at which conversion happens)",
      "Track all SAFEs on the cap table as future dilution",
      "Plan a priced round within 18–24 months of SAFE issuance",
      "Avoid stacking too many SAFEs at low caps — cumulative dilution can be severe"
    ],
    whenToUse:"In pre-seed and seed rounds where a priced round would be premature, in accelerator programmes (Y Combinator, Techstars), and in friends-and-family rounds with light documentation.",
    byWhom:"Founders raising pre-seed and seed, accelerator programme directors, angel investors, and lawyers structuring early rounds.",
    innovation:"Compared with convertible notes, the SAFE removed interest, maturity and renegotiation friction. Compared with priced equity rounds at idea stage, the SAFE deferred valuation negotiation until a priced round provided real market data.",
    figureCaption:"A timeline showing SAFE issuance (left), then a priced round 18–24 months later, with conversion mechanics: SAFE shares = SAFE amount ÷ min(cap valuation, priced-round valuation × discount).",
