    num:"F76", title:"NPV / IRR Quick Guide", unit:10, slibrary:19, pedagogy:"Business Challenge",
    author:"Irving Fisher (1907) onward",
    summary:"Discount future cash; compare to investment.",
    professionalDefinition:"Net Present Value (NPV) is the sum of discounted future cash flows minus the initial investment, with positive NPV indicating value creation; Internal Rate of Return (IRR) is the discount rate at which NPV equals zero, used for project comparison; together with payback period they form the standard toolkit for evaluating capital investments and venture economics (Fisher, 1907; Brealey, Myers & Allen, 2020).",
    whoDeveloped:"Irving Fisher (1867–1947), Yale economist, established the foundational mathematics in The Rate of Interest (1907) and The Theory of Interest (1930). Modern formalisation in corporate finance is attributable to Joel Dean (1951), Modigliani and Miller (1958), and the foundational textbook tradition exemplified by Brealey, Myers & Allen.",
    whyDeveloped:"Fisher sought to formalise the relationship between current and future consumption — and the discount rate that linked them. Subsequent corporate-finance practice extended the mathematics to project and investment evaluation, providing a defensible alternative to payback-period thinking that ignored the time value of money.",
    howToApply:[
      "Project cash flows over 5–10 years",
      "Discount at the weighted average cost of capital (WACC) or required return",
      "Sum discounted flows minus initial investment to get NPV",
      "Calculate IRR for project comparison (especially when capital is rationed)",
      "Sanity-check with payback period for liquidity-constrained contexts"
    ],
    whenToUse:"In capital-allocation decisions, business-plan financials, M&A target evaluation, and capstone financial sections.",
    byWhom:"CFOs, investment analysts, M&A teams, project managers, founders preparing financial sections of business plans.",
    innovation:"Compared with payback-period analysis (which ignores the time value of money), NPV captures the discounted value of future cash. Compared with IRR alone (which can mislead in projects with non-conventional cash flows), NPV is the more reliable single metric.",
    figureCaption:"A bar chart of cash flows over years 0–10, with year-0 negative (investment) and years 1–10 positive (returns); a discount factor curve overlaid shows the time-value adjustment producing the NPV calculation.",
